{
  "text": "The antineoplastic drugs used in the chemotherapeutic treatment do not differentiate between healthy and cancerous cells, generating a great variety of adverse effects. One of the drugs of choice as a chemotherapeutic agent is the doxorubicin (DOX) hydrochloride, a powerful anthracycline antibiotic used for more than four decades for the treatment of various types of malignancies, particularly ovarian and metastatic breast cancer [CITATION_1] . However, due to its short biological lifespan and nonspecific distribution, DOX presents severe side effects, such as hepatotoxicity, nephrotoxicity, dose-limiting myelosuppression, brain damage and significant cardiotoxicity [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , limiting its maximum doses of application. A pegylated liposomal formulation known as Doxil\u00ae was approved by the Food and Drug Agency of the United States (FDA) in 1995 [CITATION_5] , which has managed to reduce the number of cardiac events in patients with metastatic breast cancer. However, in comparison to free DOX, Doxil\u00ae has not shown significant improvements regarding survival [CITATION_6] . This performance is due mainly to the poor cellular uptake and slower DOX release from the liposomes [CITATION_7] . This latter is responsible for the reduction of adverse effects, while the first is a consequence of the presence of polyethylene-glycol (PEG) on the surface of this kind of nanoformulations. This process known as \"pegylation\" strongly inhibits the cell penetration [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] .",
